-- Market Chatter- Corporate finance press digest
-- 
-- Mon Sep 29, 2014 11:57PM EDT
-- None



Sept 30 (Reuters) - The following corporate finance-related stories were reported by media:

* New York's financial regulator wants some Commerzbank AG <CBKG.DE> employees to be fired as part of a settlement over allegations the German lender improperly processed transactions with Iran and other countries facing U.S. sanctions, according to people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0RO1US]  * China Investment Corp will raise S$396 million ($311 million) by selling about a third of its shares in commodity trader Noble Group Ltd <NOBG.SI>, a source said, sending Noble's shares down as much as 9 percent. [ID:nL3N0RV095]  * Japan's SoftBank Corp's <9984.T> talks to acquire Hollywood studio DreamWorks Animation SKG Inc <DWA.O> have cooled, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL3N0RU695]  * Boeing Co <BA.N> plans to announce further consolidation of its defense business on Tuesday, moving significant portions of its defense operations out of Washington state, according to multiple sources familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0RU1WS]  *  Marathon Petroleum Corp <MPC.N> plans to finish installing a new condensate splitter at its 80,000-barrel-per-day refinery in Canton, Ohio, by the U.S. Thanksgiving holiday, Nov. 27, three people familiar with the plans said. [ID:nL2N0RU1M8]  * Online fashion retailer Zalando <ZALG.DE> is set to price its shares at 21.50 euros ($27.28) per share for its initial public offering (IPO), sources familiar with the matter told Reuters on Monday. [ID:nL6N0RU4OW]  * Pimco executives held a global staff meeting and video conference with all employees on Monday to boost morale and discuss the $2 trillion asset manager's future, according to a source close to the situation. [ID:nL2N0RU2FZ]  (1 euro = 1.27 US dollar)  For the deals of the day click on [DEALS/]